<HL>
   Business Brief -- Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan:
   Fed Clears Underwriting,
   Dealing Through U.S. Unit
</HL>
<DATE>
05/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C21
</SO>
<CO>
   J.LTC
</CO>
<IN>
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL RESERVE BOARD (FED)
</GV>
<LP>
   The U.S. Federal Reserve System said Tokyo-based Long-Term
Credit Bank of Japan Ltd., through a subsidiary, can
underwrite and deal in certain one- to four-family
mortgage-related securities, municipal revenue bonds, and
commercial paper.
   Through Greenwich Capital Markets Inc., Greenwich, Conn.,
the bank also can underwrite and deal in consumer
receivable-related securities to a limited extent, in
futures-commission merchant activities, and the purchase and
sale of gold and silver, the Fed said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Long-Term Credit Bank is the 21st-largest bank in the
world and the 12th-largest in Japan, controlling total
consolidated assets of about $194 billion, the Fed said.
</TEXT>
